===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|de|Hamster}}, from {{der|en|gmh|hamster}}, from {{der|en|goh|hamastra}}, {{m|goh|hamustro}} (compare {{cog|osx|hamustra}}), probably from {{der|en|orv|хомѣсторъ}}, {{m|orv|хомѣстаръ}}, compound of (1) {{m|orv|хомѣкъ||hamster}} (compare {{cog|ru|хомя́к}}, {{cog|pl|chomik}}), from {{der|en|ine-bsl-pro|*kāmjas}} (compare {{cog|lv|kāmis||hamster}}, {{cog|lt|kãmas||rat}},<ref>{{R:lt:LEW|page=212}}</ref> and of (2) {{der|en|ine-bsl-pro|*staras}} (compare {{cog|lt|stãras||ground squirrel}}.<ref>Wolfgang Pfeifer, ed., ''Etymologisches Wörterbuch des Deutschen'', s.v. “Hamster” (Munich: Deutscher Taschenbucher Vertrag, 2005).</ref><ref>C.T. Onions, ed., ''Oxford Dictionary of English Etymology'', s.v. “hamster” (Oxford: Oxford UP, 1996), 425.</ref>

Alternatively, a borrowing into {{der|en|sla|-}} from {{der|en|ira|-}}, compare {{cog|ae|𐬵𐬀𐬨𐬀𐬉𐬯𐬙𐬀𐬭-|t=who throws down (in this case: corn stalks), oppresses}}.<ref>{{R:de:EWbD|Hamster}}</ref> Displaced earlier term {{m|en|German rat}}.

